5. Now suppose there are two possible climate policies that can be pursued. Policy A is business as usual and Policy B is to take immediate and strong action on climate change. Use these facts

If you undertake Policy A there are two possible outcomes. Either warming will occur as in the baseline (i.e.no-pulse) dataset above (this happens with probability 0.5) or warming each year will be 1.5 times that in the baseline dataset (with probability 0.5).

Under Policy B, warming will continue until 2050 as in the baseline dataset, and then will stabilize at 1.29 degrees and stay that way forever.

Society is risk neutral

Use a discount rate of 2%

5.1 What is the expected present value of damages up to 2100 under Policy A?

We calculated the net present value of Policy A under the baseline scenario using the net preset value formula with a 2% discount rate. We did the same thing for the case where each years temperature is multiplied by 1.5. Considering that each of these scenarios are 50% likely to happen in Policy A, we multiplied each by 0.5 and then added them together to get: $2,931,794,400,293,097

5.2 What is the expected present value of damages up to 2100 under Policy B?

We modified the data after the year 2050 to be constant at 1.29 degrees after 2050. We then calculated the net present value of the modified data so that there is still damage each year after 2050 as informed by 1.29 degree warming that already occured and so that the damage is discounted correctly back to present value. We found an expected npv for Policy B to be $709,823,683,886,657

5.3 Suppose undertaking Policy A costs zero and undertaking Policy B costs X. How large could X be for it to still make economic sense to pursue Policy B instead of Policy A?

We found that the difference between the NPV of Policy A and Policy B to be $2,221,970,716,406,440, and this is the largest amount that B could cost for it to make economic sense.

5.4 Qualitatively, how would your answer change if society were risk averse?

Under a risk neutral society you could subtract Policy A - Policy B and as long as the cost of implementing Policy B does not exceed the difference from subtracting the two policies then Policy B should be pursued and implemented. Policy B suggests that society implements costly interventions to achaive a neutral climate temperature by 2050, which in turn makes for a lower risk, or more certain outcome of lower damages. So, if society is risk averse, they would be willing to pay even more for Policy B because the utility from the certainty of Policy B is higher than the expected utility from Policy A. The exact shape of how risk averse society is will oinform how much more they might pay.
